ry America, from its origins as a consoling response to sickness to how it informed the practices of Protestant activity in the Atlantic world. Drawing on pastoral manuals, manuscript memoirs, journals, and letters, as well as medical treatises, epidemic narratives, and midwifery manuals, Koch shows how Protestant teachings around providence shaped the lives of believers even as the Enlightenment seemed to portend a more secular approach to the world and the human body. Their commitment to providence prompted, in fact, early Americans’ active engagement with the medical developments of their time, encouraging them to see modern science and medicine as divinely bestowed missionary tools for helping others. Indeed, the book shows that the ways in which the colonial world thought about questions of God’s will in sickness and health help to illuminate the continuing power of Protestant ideas and practices in American society today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aHealthxReligious aspectsxChristianityxHistoryy18th century. 0aMedicinexReligious aspectsxChristianityxHistoryy18th century. 0aMedicinezUnited StatesxHistoryy18th century. 7aRELIGION / Christianity / History.2bisacsh  aAbsalom Jones.  aAtlantic World.  aBenevolence.  aBody.  aCOVID-19.  aCharity.  aChildbirth.  aChristian Thilo.  aCivilization.  aConsolation.  aContinuity.  aCoronavirus.  aCotton Mather.  aDesign.  aDoubt.  aEmbodiment.  aEnlightenment.  aEpidemic.  aHeinrich Helmuth.  aJohn Redman.  aJohn Wesley.  aLactation.  aManuscripts.  aMartyrology.  aMaternity.  aMechanism.  aMedicine.  aMidwifery.  aMissions.  aModernity.  aNarrative.  aNature.  aNorms.  aOriginal Sin.  aPatient’s Case.  aPhiladelphia.  aPietist.  aPositive Thought.  aProvidence.  aPuritan.  